    "description": "The EXPLORE Act defines a target shooting range as a developed and managed area authorized or operated by the BLM or their lessee, specifically for the purposeful discharge by the public of legal firearms, firearms training, archery, or other associated activities. This definition includes shooting ranges transferred or leased under the Recreation and Public Purposes Act.  \n\n A qualifying range must include opportunities for rifles and pistols, include safety features like berms and buffer distances, and have a designated firing line. It may also provide opportunities for archery, skeet, trap, or sporting clays (shotgun sports), along with amenities such as shade structures, trash containers, restrooms, and benches.  \n\nBLM has identified 93 qualifying ranges, with 76% of districts (38 out of 50) having one. No districts are restricted from constructing or transferring land for a range, while 12 districts need to establish qualifying ranges. BLM assessments, along with outreach to Western Governors’ Offices and state fish and game agencies, have identified 36 additional potential ranges needed.  ",
